					A wooden statue found at Abydos, one of ancient Egypt’s holiest sites, was likely used in ceremonial processions honoring the underworld god Osiris. Since the figurine has feminine features, it might represent the powerful female pharaoh Hatshepsut, who was often depicted as a man. (Credit: Mary-Ann Pouls Wegner)
